<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
This species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. conspersa" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="conspersa">P. conspersa</taxonomicName>
(O. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pickard–Cambridge">Pickard-Cambridge</normalizedToken>
, 1876). Males are diagnosed by the different shape of the base of the tegular apophysis (sub-circular in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. dalmasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="dalmasi">P. dalmasi</taxonomicName>
vs. irregularly shaped in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. conspersa" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="conspersa">P. conspersa</taxonomicName>
) and the retrolateral tibial apophysis (more massive in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. conspersa" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="conspersa">P. conspersa</taxonomicName>
), while females can be distinguished by the different shape of the epigynal septum (anterior depression pointed posteriorly and median curves pointed anteriorly or anterolaterally in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. dalmasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="dalmasi">P. dalmasi</taxonomicName>
(Figs 1d, e) vs. the anterior depression pointed anteriorly and median curves pointed posteriorly in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. conspersa" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="conspersa">P. conspersa</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, G" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="919 - 981" title="Revision of the spider subfamily Gnaphosinae in Israel (Araneae: Gnaphosidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222939500770351" volume="29" year="1995">Levy 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
